body:
I'd move everything from American to your choice of Fidelity, Schwab, or Vanguard. All 3 offer great index funds and target date index funds of their own with very low (and in the case for 4 Fidelity funds, even no) expense ratios.

&amp;#x200B;

Fidelity and Schwab do have mutual funds that are much easier to get into, with only $1 initial and ongoing required. I'd also personally prefer these 2 since they offer more than Vanguard: 24/7 customer service, checking or cash management accounts with ATM fee refunds (Vanguard closed the closest thing they had over the summer, and even then, it was much more limited than Fidelity or Schwab's offerings), and both offer optional credit cards if you wish. For stocks and ETFs, Fidelity is in the process of rolling out fractional shares over the next few weeks, Schwab has announced it but has not started a rollout yet (I believe I heard spring?).

&amp;#x200B;

You should open a high yield savings account in addition to everything else, possibly except if you go with Fidelity or Schwab and use their CMA or checking accounts (since you can invest money there in money market funds which should return similar to a HYSA, but you do give up FDIC or NCUA insurance by doing this).
